web_research.query: What are winning approaches for image classification competitions on Kaggle with small 32x32 images?
web_research.finding: Winning Kaggle solutions for 32 × 32 image tasks (e.g., CIFAR‑10 style competitions) combine a **strong, well‑regularized CNN baseline** with aggressive **data‑augmentation, careful hyper‑parameter tuning, and model‑level ensembling**.  A common starting point is a small‑resolution‑friendly architecture such as ResNet‑18/34, Wide‑ResNet, or EfficientNet‑B0 that is either trained from scratch or fine‑tuned from ImageNet weights using the “bottleneck‑features + top‑layer fine‑tuning” recipe described by Chollet (2016) ([keras.io](https://blog.keras.io/building-powerful-image-classification-models-using-very-little-data.html)).  Because 32 × 32 images provide very little spatial information, heavy augmentation (random crops, horizontal flips, color jitter, CutMix/MixUp) is essential to prevent over‑fitting and to expose the model to diverse patterns ([Towards Data Science, 2019](https://towardsdatascience.com/latest-winning-techniques-for-kaggle-image-classification-with-limited-data-5259
